<br>
I never could quite express how I wanted you to be free from bindings, not bind you to ways that aren't on your path.  It's why I always felt bad that you wanted things I couldn't give you, worshipped in a way I never could.  I wanted us to help each other learn how to open our eyes wider to see things more clearly, but so often it seemed we couldn't even see the same things to begin with.  I didn't want to just turn your head to what I saw, and I never knew how to describe it...<br>
<br>
I still can't explain why I felt you needed to go.  I don't even know why I'm trying to explain it to myself now, unless there's still that spark of you inside who will sometimes turn to me with questions.  I wish I could give you the answers you need, or even just the ones you're looking for.  It would help me feel like I can still give you something greater than the freedom to give to yourself.  That part of each other that pledged 'forever' will forever be sealed inside of us, but I feel it locked away now in your darkest corner, waiting, wishing...<br>
<br>
I hope you do your part for the world, and I hope it's easier for you without worrying about trying not to worry who else may be treasured within my heart, and why I value them the way I do.  I hope you never succumb to another god trying to control you, and I hope if you choose to anyway, that I can simply let your choice be.  I hope when your work is all done, your spirit will be free, and we can talk again about how things change.  I hope if there's ever another way I can help you, I hope you'll let me help.  <br>
<br>
I hope...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Kimaya let her thoughts trail off into a swirl of colors and images beyond the description of words, lost in the flowing flood of feeling and impressions of gifts now past, gifts unopened and gifts she'd never be allowed to give.  After an unmeasured moment, she let this flood flow past her, into the sea, where it may merge with all the other dreams and possibilities that had yet to be brought ashore.<br>
<br>
She looked down into her hand to ponder the small, rosy shell she had clasped into her lap as her mind was occupied, sealing the thoughts, hopes and memories within.  She then reached out and let it slip into the water, wishing that it may perhaps find its way to her 'nuzzles' someday, perhaps may speak again to his soul, or perhaps even simply rest with Prexus as another treasure forever lost at sea.  And again, as always, she wasn't sure which should be true, and was glad it wasn't her choice to make.<br>
<br>
She nodded to the waves as they crashed upon the shore, then whispered the words that would call out her Kazzybear.  Soon, little elf and bear feet had scampered down the beach, leaving nothing but faint shifts in the pattern of the sand. <p><p align="center">
